\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional Hilbert Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The irreducible states in a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional Hilbert space are encoded in a similar family of geometric
 structures known technically as the complex projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We obtain these structures starting with the 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 initially unnormalized complex coefficients of the 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\alpha_{i}\ket{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We then follow the analog of the two-dimensional procedure: conservation
 of probability requires that the norm of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\VVec{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 be normalized to unity: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{\Psi}{\Psi}=\left\Vert \VVec{\alpha}\right\Vert ^{2}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}|\alpha_{i}|^{2}=1\,.\label{probEq1.eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the initial equation for the geometry of a quantum state describes
 a 
\shape italic
topological sphere
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\shape default

\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

 embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathReal^{2D}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, remember that we can write the real and imaginary parts of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=x_{i}+\rmi y_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}|\alpha_{i}|^{2}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}{x_{i}}^{2}+{y_{i}}^{2}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

describes the locus of a 
\begin_inset Formula $2D$
\end_inset

-dimensional real unit vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathReal^{2D}$
\end_inset

, which is by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $(2D-1)$
\end_inset

-sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

 is ambiguous up to the usual overall phase, inducing an 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{1}$
\end_inset

 symmetry action, and identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{1}$
\end_inset

 bundle, whose base space is the 
\begin_inset Formula $(D-1)$
\end_inset

-complex-dimensional projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

.
 There are thus 
\begin_inset Formula $2D-2$
\end_inset

 irreducible real degrees of freedom (
\begin_inset Formula $D-1$
\end_inset

 complex degrees of freedom) for a quantum state with a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\set{\ket{i}}{i=0,\ldots,D-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, the full space of a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional quantum state, including its overall phase defining its relationshi
p to other quantum states, is the topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For an isolated system, the overall phase is not measurable, and eliminating
 the phase dependence corresponds to identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2D-1}$
\end_inset

 as a circle bundle over the base space 
\begin_inset Formula $\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

 defines the 
\begin_inset Formula $2D-2$
\end_inset

 intrinsic, irreducible, degrees of freedom of the isolated 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional state's dynamics.
 In mathematical notation, this would be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{1}\hookrightarrow\Sphere{2D-1}\rightarrow\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
