\begin_layout Standard
Given a finite sample space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 representing all possible outcomes of a process, and its power set 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 as the classical event space, a classical probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 maps every event 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

 to a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E\right)\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 specifying how likely one of the outcomes in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 will happen.
 To maintain the coherence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is subject to the following constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\emptyset\right)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\overline{E}\right)=1-\mu\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 is the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
  Moreover, we require 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E_{0}\cup E_{1}\right)=\mu\left(E_{0}\right)+\mu\left(E_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for each pair of disjoint events 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the previous abstraction doesn't specify the process to generate the
 outcomes, this process could well be a quantum experiment.
 Let us prepare a beam of one kind of spin
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 particles whose state can be characterized by a vector in three-dimensional
 Hilbert space with basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In principle, this beam can be split by a Stern-Gerlach type experiment
 according to the eigenvalues of the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}_{0}$
\end_inset

 with spectral decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{O}_{0}=0\,\proj{0}+1\,\proj{1}+2\,\proj{2}\,,\label{eq:observable}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the states corresponding to the split beams are 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key ":/content/aip/journal/jmp/21/1/10.1063/1.524312,peres1995quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Instead of sending a beam of particles, if only one particle is sent to
 the beam splitter, the state of the particle after the experiment is one
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

, and there is a probability to get each post-experimental state.
 In the language of our abstraction, the set of outcomes is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}=\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 All possible events are 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{1},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 And this experiment defines a classical probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}\colon2^{\Omega_{0}}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One special feature of quantum experiments is that the probabilities in
 different experiments are correlated.
 Consider another experiment sending exactly the same particle as the previous
 one but using a different beam splitter corresponding to the observable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}_{1}$
\end_inset

 with spectral decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}_{1}=0\,\proj{\ps}+1\,\proj{\ms}+2\,\proj{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}=\frac{\ket{0}+\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ms}=\frac{\ket{0}-\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Although the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}=\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}\colon2^{\Omega_{1}}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 defined by this experiment is different from the previous one, these two
 experiments may produce the same post-experimental state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

, and the probability of the common event 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is believed to be the same, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{0}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)=\mu_{1}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)\,.\label{eq:mu0-equal-mu1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In general, as long as sending the same particle, the probability of the
 same event in different experiments should always be the same.
 This fact is equivalent to the fact that commuting observables could be
 measured simultaneously which is essential to define contextuality and
 will be explained in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Kochen-Specker"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the probability induced by the different beam splitters are correlated,
 it is more natural to define one quantum event space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 containing all possible classical event spaces using different beam splitters.
 However, simply taking the union of all event spaces is a bad idea because
 two events might appear different but represent the same situation.
 For example, if we take the complement on both sides of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mu0-equal-mu1"

\end_inset

), we will have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{0}\left(\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} \right)=1-\mu_{0}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)=1-\mu_{1}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)=\mu_{1}\left(\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms}\right\} \right)\,,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that is, the probabilities of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are always the same, and these events should be identified as the same
 quantum event to simplify our discussion.
 This identification can be achieved by mapping a classical event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to the projector generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\left(E\right)=\sum_{\ket{j}\in E}\proj{j}\label{eq:pullback-function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(\emptyset\right)=\mathbb{0}$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 as operators,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi\left(\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} \right)=\proj{0}+\proj{1}=\proj{\ps}+\proj{\ms}=\varphi\left(\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms}\right\} \right)\,.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In general, if two classical events
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

 are mapped to the same projector, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(E\right)=\varphi\left(E'\right)$
\end_inset

, then the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the same as the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, for any classical event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, its corresponding quantum event is defined to be the projector 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

, and the set of all projectors on a given Hilbert space is called a quantum
 event space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

.
 
