\begin_layout Standard
We have thus quantified one important aspect of uncertainty in quantum mechanics
—the effect of the imprecise nature of devices—which is a novel addition
 to the theory of measurement.
 Indeed, as Heisenberg emphasized in his famous microscope example
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heisenberg1983"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the conventional theory of measurement states that it is impossible to
 precisely measure any property of a system without disturbing it somewhat.
 Thus, there are fundamental limits to what one can measure and these limits
 have traditionally been attributed to complementarity.
 Our imprecision represents an 
\emph on
additional
\emph default
 source of indeterminacy beyond the inherent probabilistic nature of quantum
 mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an experimental setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is calculated as follows.
 To determine the probability of any event, we typically repeat an experiment
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times and count the number of times we witness the event.
 This assumes that for each run of the experiment we can determine, using
 our apparatus, whether the event occurred or not.
 Assume an event has an ideal mathematical probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, and we repeat the experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 times.
 In a perfect world, we should be able to refute the event 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 times and calculate that the probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 We might also observe the event 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 times and refute it 
\begin_inset Formula $98$
\end_inset

 times and therefore calculate the probability to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this situation assumes perfect measurement conditions and remains
 within the context of conventional (real-valued) probability theory.
 The question we focus on is what happens if we are only able to refute
 it 
\begin_inset Formula $97$
\end_inset

 times and are 
\emph on
uncertain
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 times? This is quite common in actual experiments.
 Mathematically we can model this idea by stating that the probability of
 the event is in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0.03\right]$
\end_inset

 which says that the probability of the event could be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

 as each the three uncertain records could either be evidence for the event
 or against it.
 We just cannot nail it down given the current experimental results and
 therefore represent the evidence as a (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

-deterministic probability measure.
 The interesting observation is that the axioms of probability theory (like
 additivity and convexity) impose enough constraints on the structure of
 interval-valued quantum probability measures to make them robust in the
 face of small non-vanishing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

's.
\end_layout

